◆ ADDR_AINC

◆ ADDR_MSK

__IOM uint32_t R_ETHSW_Type::ADDR_MSK

[11..0] Memory address for read and write transactions. This is the address of a 69-bit entry. For the DEL_PORT bit, a port mask can be provided in these bits instead of the address. Bit 0 represents port 0, bit 1 port 1, and so on.

◆ CLEAR

__IOM uint32_t R_ETHSW_Type::CLEAR

[29..29] When set to 1, writes all 0s to the entry selected by the given address set in ADDR_MSK[11:0]. If this bit is set together with the LOOKUP bit, first a lookup is performed and if the lookup succeeds, the entry is then deleted. The registers LK_DATA_LO/HI/HI2 are also cleared. The memory address in this register is set from the lookup result. If the lookup failed, the clear command is ignored and memory address is arbitrary.

[29..29] When set to 1, write all 0s to the entry selected by the given address.

◆ CLEAR_DYNAMIC

◆ CLEAR_ON_READ

◆ CMP16

__IOM uint32_t R_ETHSW_Type::CMP16

[28..28] When set, MASK_VAL2[7:0] is used as a value to perform a 16-bit compare. COMPARE_VAL[7:0] represent the byte at the given offset and MASK_VAL2[7:0] represent the byte following at offset + 1 which matches the network byte order for 16-bit fields. For example, setting a compare value of 0x0800 and offset 0 matches IP frames. No mask is available in this mode.

[28..28] When set, MASK_VAL2[7:0] is used as a value to perform a 16-bit compare. COMPARE_VAL[7:0] represents the byte at the given offset and MASK_VAL2[7:0] represents the byte following at offset + 1 which matches the network byte order for 16-bit fields, (for example setting a compare value of 0x0800 and offset 0 matches IP frames). No mask is available in this mode.

◆ CMP_MASK_OR

__IOM uint32_t R_ETHSW_Type::CMP_MASK_OR

[30..30] Use the MASK_VAL2[7:0] bits as a 2nd compare value. When set, the parser reports a match if the byte at given offset matches COMPARE_VAL[7:0] or MASK_VAL2[7:0].

[30..30] Use MASK_VAL2[7:0] as a second compare value. When set, the parser reports a match if the byte at given offset matches COMPARE_VAL[7:0] or MASK_VAL2[7:0].

◆ CT_OVR

__IOM uint32_t R_ETHSW_Type::CT_OVR

[18..16] 1 bit per-port value to set the Cut Through behavior of the output ports. When set to 0, all frames are sent as Store & Forward (SF) frames. When set to 1, frames with the CT flag set in the frame context are started as soon as the frame context information is available.

◆ CT_OVR_ENA

__IOM uint32_t R_ETHSW_Type::CT_OVR_ENA

[2..0] Per-port bit mask to enable overriding the Cut-Through (CT) behavior of the output ports with CT_OVR. When set to 0, the frames are transmitted CT if the CT flag of the frame context is set.

◆ CTFL_EMPTY_MD

◆ ENABLE

__IOM uint32_t R_ETHSW_Type::ENABLE

[6..6] If set, all Bridge Protocol Frames (BPDU) are forwarded exclusively to the management port specified in bits [3:0].

[0..0] Enable Management Tag Insertion Module

[0..0] ENABLE

[31..31] Write to 1 to enable the Link Queue Trigger feature. When the link status (phy_link) transitions from 1 -> 0, a trigger event is generated to the memory controller for the ports and queues indicated in PORT_MASK and QUEUE_MASK.

[0..0] Enable DLR extension module. When set, the DLR module becomes active. When DLR is enabled, the LOOP_FILTER_ENA must also be enabled for proper DLR operation.

◆ HUB_DEFPORT

__IOM uint32_t R_ETHSW_Type::HUB_DEFPORT

(@ 0x00003E08) HUB Default Port Selection Register

[2..0] The default port within the Hub Group where all traffic from a port outside the group is forwarded to port (bit 0 = port 0, bit 1 = port 1, and bit 2 = port 2). If a frame should be forwarded to any of the hub ports, the frame is sent to this port only. The copy function of the hub copies it to all PHY interfaces of the group eventually.

◆ IGNORE_INVTM

__IOM uint32_t R_ETHSW_Type::IGNORE_INVTM

[4..4] Enable ignore beacon frames with invalid timeout timer. When enabled (set to 1) frames with timeout timer value not within a range of 200 microseconds to 500 milliseconds are ignored and parameters are not locally stored or considered for state transitions. The invalid timeout timer value is always stored within the DLR_INV_TMOUT register irrespective of the value of this bit. Ignored frames are forwarded normally.

◆ IPPROTOCOL

__IOM uint32_t R_ETHSW_Type::IPPROTOCOL

[27..27] When set, the compare value is compared with the protocol field found within the IP header for both IPv4 and IPv6 frames. It implicitly acts as SKIPVLAN = 1 skipping any VLAN tags if present. The offset setting has no meaning and is ignored.

[27..27] When set, the compare value is compared with the protocol field located within the IP header for both IPv4 and IPv6 frames. It implicitly acts as SKIPVLAN = 1 skipping any VLAN tags if present. The offset setting has no meaning and is ignored. If the bit is set, but the frame is not an IPv4/v6 frame the parser reports a no match and does not continue to inspect the frame. When cleared, the offset is used normally on all frames.

◆ MASK_VAL2

__IOM uint32_t R_ETHSW_Type::MASK_VAL2

[7..0] Mask for single byte compares or 2nd compare value (if bit 30 = 1) or least significant bits of a 16-bit compare value (if bit 28 = 1). When used as a mask (bit 28, 30 = 0, 0), the data from the frame is ANDed with this mask, then compared to the compare value. All bits having a 1 in the mask will be compared with the data in the frame. All bits having a 0 will be 0 for the compare, however this requires the compare value to have those bits also set to 0.

[7..0] Mask for single byte compares or 2nd compare value (if bit 30 = 1) or least significant bits of a 16-bit compare value (if bit 28 = 1). When used as a mask (bit 28, 30 = 0, 0), the data from the frame is ANDed with this mask, then compared to the compare value. All bits having a 1 in the mask are compared with the data in the frame. All bits having a 0 will be 0 for the compare, however this requires the compare value to have those bits also set to 0.

◆ MATCH_LT

__IOM uint32_t R_ETHSW_Type::MATCH_LT

[25..25] For operating modes 1, 2, and 3. When set to 1, the Length/Type field in the frame after the MAC source address is compared against the value in length_type in the compare register. If VLAN_SKIP is set and the frame has a VLAN tag with Length/Type of 0x8100 then the comparison is performed in the Length/Type following the VLAN tag.

◆ OFFSET

__IOM uint32_t R_ETHSW_Type::OFFSET

[21..16] An offset in bytes where to find the data for comparison within the frame. The offset value starts at 0 to indicate the very first byte after offset start. The offset start can be either the type/length field of the frame, that is, 0 = first byte of type/length field) or the payload following an IP header (see IPDATA). Valid values range from 0 to 60.

[21..16] An offset in bytes to locate the data for comparison within the frame. The offset value starts at 0 to indicate the very first byte after offset start. The offset start can be either the type or length field of the frame, for example 0 = first byte of type/length field) or the payload following an IP header (see bit 26). Valid values range from 0 to 60.

[31..0] Value used for performing offset corrections without changing the drift correction

◆ OFFSET_DA

__IOM uint32_t R_ETHSW_Type::OFFSET_DA

[23..23] When set, the offset starts counting from the first byte of the MAC destination address.

◆ OFFSET_PLUS2

__IOM uint32_t R_ETHSW_Type::OFFSET_PLUS2

[29..29] Repeats the comparison at offset + 2, if the comparison at offset failed.

◆ ONE_SHOT

__IOM uint32_t R_ETHSW_Type::ONE_SHOT

[1..1] Avoid timer wrap around. If set, the timer stops at maximum. An overflow interrupt (TSM_CONFIG.IRQ_ATIME_OVER) occurs (if enabled) when the maximum is reached.

◆ OP

__IOM uint32_t R_ETHSW_Type::OP

[16..16] Operation

◆ OP_ERR

__IM uint32_t R_ETHSW_Type::OP_ERR

[3..0] A frame cannot be stored in an output queue of the port as the queue FIFO overflowed (write occurred into full fifo). The frame is ignored but stays stored in memory. This should not occur during normal operation. This is a fatal error as the memory allocated by that frame is not freed, and resulting in memory leakage.

[3..3] Output Cut-Through Enable

◆ PORT_ENA

__IOM uint32_t R_ETHSW_Type::PORT_ENA

(@ 0x00000008) Port Enable Register

[3..0] Set to 1 to indicate that a port is operating in TDMA mode. When set to 1 for a port, the port does not prefetch another frame until the current frame in progress is done and if TDMA_PREBUF_DIS in COMMAND_CONFIG is set to 1. This helps adding precision to the queue gating operations indicated by the TDMA at the expense of loss of line rate.

◆ 

struct { ... } R_ETHSW_Type::PORT_ENA_b

◆ PORT_MASK [1/2]

__IOM uint32_t R_ETHSW_Type::PORT_MASK

[3..0] Per-port Bit Mask

◆ PORT_MASK [2/2]

__OM uint32_t R_ETHSW_Type::PORT_MASK

[3..0] Per-port bit mask. When set to 1 for a port, the queue gate state is changed for that port as indicated by QUEUE_GATE.

[3..0] Per-port bit mask. When set to 1 for a port, a frame is triggered from the closed queues indicated by QUEUE_TRIG.

[3..0] Per-port bit mask. When set to 1 for a port, the queue flush status is changed for that port for the queues indicated in QUEUE_MASK.

◆ PORTMASK

__IOM uint32_t R_ETHSW_Type::PORTMASK

[19..16] Portmask for transmission of management frames. When the management port transmits a frame to the switch, it is forwarded to all ports in this portmask (bit 16 = port 0, bit 17 = port 1, ..., bit 19 = port 3).

[3..0] When this bit is set to 1, it defines a port as a member of the VLAN. When bit [28] or bit [29] is set, the tagged bit mask is read/written instead of port mask.

[19..16] A port mask used depending on the control bits (for example, HUBTRIGGER).

◆ PREEMPT_ON_QCLOSE

[15..8] Per-queue configuration bit to enable preempting a frame when the queue goes from OPEN to CLOSED. When the corresponding bit is set to 1 and the queue is configured as preemptable in PREEMPT_ENA, a queue close event causes the current frame to be preempted, if preemption is operational.

◆ Q_1FRAME_ENA

__IOM uint32_t R_ETHSW_Type::Q_1FRAME_ENA

◆ QUEUE_SEL0

__IOM uint32_t R_ETHSW_Type::QUEUE_SEL0

[10..8] Select which two physical queues are used for CQF. The queues used are QUEUE_SEL0 and QUEUE_SEL0 + 1. Frames are written into QUEUE_SEL0 when the gate control selected with GATE_SEL0 is 0, and into QUEUE_SEL0 + 1 when the gate control is 1.

◆ QUEUE_TRIG

__OM uint32_t R_ETHSW_Type::QUEUE_TRIG

[23..16] 1-bit per queue indicating from which queues a frame is to be transmitted from the ports indicated by PORT_MASK. When set to 1, a single frame is transmitted per indicated port in PORT_MASK among the queues indicated by QUEUE_TRIG.

◆ QUEUESEL

[31..28] A queue selector for the HUBTRIGGER function. Selects the queue to trigger a frame, or sets from 0x8 to 0xF to select one among all queues.

◆ RESET

__IOM uint32_t R_ETHSW_Type::RESET

[31..31] When set to 1, all internal functions are aborted and return to a stable state (flushes prescalers). It also triggers a clear of all counter memory (all ports are cleared) by setting STATN_CONTROL.CMD_CLEAR with all mask bits. Capture memory is not reset.

[2..2] When set to 1 prevents the MAC from responding to "verify" frames.

◆ RX_BR_SMD_DIS

__IOM uint32_t R_ETHSW_Type::RX_BR_SMD_DIS

[17..17] When set to 1, the receiver does not decode the 802.3br SMDs and assumes all frames are express frames. This bit must be set to 0 for correct operation with 802.3br, and can be set to 1 when 802.3br is not enabled to avoid false detection of SMDs.

◆ RX_STRICT_BR_CTL

__IOM uint32_t R_ETHSW_Type::RX_STRICT_BR_CTL

[18..18] When set to 1, strict checking of VERIFY and RESPONSE frames is enabled. When set to 1, the frame contents and frame length checks are also performed on these frames. The mCRC is always checked regardless of the value of this register. This bit must be set to 0 to be compliant with the functionality described in IEEE 802.3br.

◆ RX_STRICT_PRE

__IOM uint32_t R_ETHSW_Type::RX_STRICT_PRE

[16..16] When set to 1, the preamble is checked so all bytes except the SFD are 0x55. When set to 0, only the last 2 bytes of the preamble are checked (SFD/SMD and FRAG_COUNT). It is recommended to set this bit to 1 to comply with the 802.3br specification. This bit must be set to 0 if only non-802.3br traffic is expected (for example, normal Ethernet traffic) and if custom preamble is used.

◆ RX_TRIGGER

[2..0] Interrupt Pending Indication

◆ SWAP_BYTES

__IOM uint32_t R_ETHSW_Type::SWAP_BYTES

[24..24] Applicable only for operating modes 1, 2, and 3. When set to 1, the byte order is swapped from the order received by the frame. ◆ TDMA_START

__IOM uint32_t R_ETHSW_Type::TDMA_START

(@ 0x00003E88) TDMA Start Time Set Register

[31..0] Set the start time for the very first cycle after system initialization has completed. The value is compared with the system time (selected in TDMA_CONFIG.TIMER_SEL) and when it is reached (crossed), the scheduler begins with its first cycle. The 2nd cycle is then at TDMA_START + TDMA_CYCLE.

__IOM uint32_t R_ETHSW_Type::TIMER_SEL

◆ US_TIME

__IOM uint32_t R_ETHSW_Type::US_TIME

[19..8] Number of clock cycles required for 1 microsecond for the switch operating clock. This LSI operates at 200 MHz, therefore this register must be set to 0xC8. The value after reset must be changed.

◆ USE_SOP0

[14..14] When set to 1, the CFQ queue is determined when the SOP is received at the frame writer in the memory controller. When set to 0, the queue is determined when the EOP is received at the frame writer.

[25..16] Reports the current available number of used cells for this memory pool. The used number of free cells can be calculated as CELLS - USED.

__IOM uint32_t R_ETHSW_Type::VLAN_SKIP

[11..11] When set to 1, for operating modes 1, 2, and 3. The first Length/Type after the MAC source address is compared against 0x8100. If it matches, a VLAN tag is assumed and 4 bytes are skipped.

◆ VLANID

__IOM uint32_t R_ETHSW_Type::VLANID

[15..4] The 12-bit VLAN identifier (VLAN ID) of the entry.

[11..0] Configure the VLAN ID to be used for VLAN n (n: IALK_VLAN_CONFIG.VLANS ENABLED). This bit is only valid when VLANID_ENA bit is set to 1. A value of 0 matches any VLAN ID.

[27..27] When set to 1, instructs to stall the processor bus until the transaction is completed. This allows performing of consecutive writes into this register with varying commands without the need for polling the BUSY bit.

◆ YELLOW_LEN

__IOM uint32_t R_ETHSW_Type::YELLOW_LEN

[15..2] Length in bytes of the YELLOW period for port n. Determines whether a frame can be transmitted before the YELLOW period expires. The value is programmed in increments of 4 bytes excluding the MAC overhead (IPG, Preamble and FCS if appended) of the frame.

◆ YLEN_EN

__IOM uint32_t R_ETHSW_Type::YLEN_EN

[16..16] When set to 1, enables transmission when OUT_CT_ENA is low only if the frame length is less than YELLOW_LEN. If cleared, YELLOW_LEN is ignored and frames are always transmitted in SF mode when OUT_CT_ENA is 0.
